{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01QgX33ZpHmAuTbc6cZUYVDt","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Done. CockroachDB metrics are now being scraped by Prometheus.\n\n## What I did\n\nThe cluster runs the **Prometheus Operator**, with a `Prometheus` CR named `crdb` in `monitoring` whose `serviceMonitorSelector: {}` and `serviceMonitorNamespaceSelector: {matchNames: [cockroachdb]}` mean it picks up any `ServiceMonitor` in the `cockroachdb` namespace.\n\nSo I created a **ServiceMonitor** (`cockroachdb/cockroachdb`) targeting the `crdb-cluster` service, port `http` (8080), path `/_status/vars`, scheme `http` (the cluster is insecure — HTTPS returns nothing, HTTP returns 200). I added a `keep` relabeling on `__meta_kubernetes_service_name` so only the headless `crdb-cluster` service is scraped — without it, the identical labels on `crdb-cluster-public` caused every pod to be scraped twice.\n\n## Verification\n\n1. **Active targets** — Prometheus reports 3 active targets (one per CockroachDB pod), all `health: up`:\n   - `http://10.244.0.31:8080/_status/vars`, `.32`, `.33`\n2. **Endpoint reachable in-cluster** — `curl http://crdb-cluster:8080/_status/vars` from a pod returns `200`; `up{job=\"crdb-cluster\"}` = `1` for all 3 instances, and real CockroachDB metrics (e.g. `sql_conns`) are being ingested.\n\nThe ServiceMonitor manifest is at `/tmp/crdb-servicemonitor.yaml` and is applied to the cluster."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":523,"cache_read_input_tokens":39301,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":523},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0ac044aa-b7eb-45c9-b957-5e89cb154bd9","uuid":"971b28e0-1ff3-4b28-92f6-2f8313d6e2e6","request_id":"req_011CcApYhxgMyzxnBT3